      <prefercite id="aspace_176116adc72f4635932a190c198cc5d8">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
         <p>Samuel Gruenberg Papers (MS 1804). Manuscripts and Archives, Yale University Library.</p>  
      </prefercite>
      <bioghist id="aspace_bfdfc55fff977dd16e207fe861bd804a">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Born in Romania, Samuel Gruenberg (1879-1959) was a rabbi, biblical scholar, and religious Zionist activist in Berlin, where he lived until 1939, when he emigrated to Palestine. He was active in the Mizrachi (religious Zionist) movement and after his arrival in Palestine, he served as the chairman of the Religious Council (Mo'atsah Datit) of Tel Aviv.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_7361eae041aeb13219428f40d168d7e5">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The collection consists of correspondence, organizational records, personal papers, daily calendars, photographs, sermons, poetry, research materials, and other writings that document the activities and research of Samuel Gruenberg.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
